    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im buying a house in austin and the seller is asking for earnest money but the title company says it has to go into an escrow account first. why can't i just give it to them or keep it in my own account until we close? seems like a lot of extra steps.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Earnest money, a good-faith deposit, is a necessary step in the process, and it's usually handled through an escrow account for a few reasons. It ensures that both sides are serious, and it protects everyone involved, especially if things go south. Think of it like a shared, secure holding spot for the initial agreement.\n\nThe title company is right to insist on escrow because it keeps the funds separate and neutral until all the legal paperwork is finalized. If you just hand the money directly to the seller, there's no official record of that initial commitment, and if the deal falls apart, it's a mess. It's just a standard procedure for making sure everyone plays by the rules.",
